The paper uses deep learning-based visual analysis to estimate person-specific behavior parameters, which suggests that it belongs to the computer vision (cs.CV) sub-category. Additionally, the paper utilizes game theory to model the interdependent decision-making process of multiple pedestrians, which suggests that it belongs to the artificial intelligence (cs.AI) sub-category. The paper also uses machine learning techniques to build predictive models, which suggests that it belongs to the machine learning (cs.LG) sub-category. The paper deals with the dynamics of pedestrian interactions, which suggests that it belongs to the social and information networks (cs.SI) sub-category. Finally, the paper deals with the modeling of pedestrian behavior, which suggests that it belongs to the robotics (cs.RO) sub-category.
